posts.name: sam liu
posts.cooked: The project demonstrates a realistic simulation of a Java robot competing in a driving-like game. Built on the 2024 Beijing WRC Off-Season Event, it utilizes WPILib Physics Simulation for accurate mechanical modeling, PhotonLib Simulation for vision systems, and detailed chassis calculations. Additionally, AI capabilities allow for training strategies like feed-and-shoot drills. The project is hosted on GitHub under the Shenzhen-Robotics-Alliance repository.

posts.name: Jim Sokoloff
posts.cooked: I think I fixed more than half of my issue. Drag the Robot 2D pose onto the 3D field. That allows me to drive around a robot, though I still don't have the 3D Shooter mechanism. But that doesn't stop me from achieving what I want to do this week. This really amazes me.

posts.name: sam liu
posts.cooked: The 'swerve skeleton' is our core swerve drive code. The physics sim stuff started out built directly into the skeleton as utility classes. We later created 'MapleSim' as a general library to make the physics simulation easily usable by anyone, no matter what code base they use.
